info.name: Censys ASM
info.description:
# Overview

The Censys Platform API is a REST-based interface that allows customers to interact programmatically with their seed list, and to view discovered assets , logbook events about those assets, risks, and statistics about their public cloud usage. Customers can also manage assets with tagging and comments.

# Authentication

Each API request is authenticated with an API key, which can be found on the [Integrations page](https://app.censys.io/integrations) of the app.

item.name: Assets

request.description: Lists all certificates associated to your organization, as well as third-party certificates presented by hosts associated to your organization.

item.description:
# Introduction

The asset API lists all discovered assets of a type and returns individual assets when requested.

## Asset Types

* Certificates
* Domains
* Hosts

Common fields in all asset type entities include:

* `type` (enum) - One of three asset types.
    * Members:
        * `CERT`
        * `DOMAIN`
        * `HOST`
* `assetId` (string) - The natural ID of the asset, given its type.
* `isSeed` (boolean) - Indicator of whether the asset was provided as a seed.
* `tags` (array[string]) - A collection of user-appended tags on the asset.
* `risks` (array[object]) - A collection of risks uncovered for the asset.

Type-specific fields are returned in a `data` object.

item.description:
# Introduction

The Cloud API endpoints provide asset counts by Cloud Service Provider to enable cloud security evaluation.

## Cloud Definitions

For these endpoints, a `cloud` is a list of public Cloud Service Provider.

Members:
* `Amazon AWS`
* `Google Cloud`
* `Microsoft Azure`
* `Alibaba Cloud`
* `SoftLayer Technologies. Inc.`
* `Tencent Cloud`
* `Digital Ocean, Inc`
* `Hetzner Online`
* `Verizon Communications Inc.`
* `Oracle Cloud`
* `Huawei Cloud Service`
* `US Signal`
* `otherCloud` - A combination of all of the clouds in the list, minus `Amazon AWS`, `Google Cloud`, and `Microsoft Azure`.
* `other` - Non-cloud datacenters

### Cloud Hosts

A cloud host is an IPv4 address that is part of a netblock or autonomous system allocated to one of the Cloud Service Providers listed above.

### Cloud Domains

A cloud domain is a domain name that is present in a nameserver run by one of the Cloud Service Providers listed above.

### Cloud Subdomains

A cloud subdomain is a subdomain of a cloud domain.

### Cloud Storage Objects

A cloud storage object is a storage bucket, known as AWS S3 buckets, GCP Storage, or Azure blobs.

Submits a list of event types and a date to begin pulling from and returns a cursor to poll the logbook with.

The cursor will retrieve events of the types submitted in this call from the specified date when used as a query paramenter on `GET /logbbook`.

## Introduction
The Logbook is a change log of activity related to your assets. 

The Censys Logbook REST API allows Censys Platform customers to poll the logbook for changes in their attack surface that meet their interest.

You can retrieve all logbook events of all types from all time by calling the `/logbook` endpoint, which will return a new cursor as part of the payload to use in the next request for the next page.

### Filtering Logbook Events

Logbook events have types and subtypes, and the types can be set as a filter when creating a logbook cursor.

To filter logbook events by type, or to pull events from a specified time or event ID, you must create a cursor. You will provide the cursor as a query parameter on a GET request to the logbook endpoint, which will return a new cursor as part of the payload to use in the next request.


## Event Types
Patterns of event types and subtypes that appear in the logbook are due to the relationships between the event types.
### `HOST`

Events of this type are related to the inclusion or exclusion of IP addresses in your organization's attack surface.

* **Subtype `ASSOCIATE`** - An IP address was added to your organization's asset collection.

* **Subtype `DISASSOCIATE`** - An IP address was removed from your organization's asset collection.

Cascading Event Types That Could Follow a Host Event

Subtype would match the Host event, (e.g. _Host Associate_ would be followed by _Add_ events, and _Host Disassociate_ would be followed by _Remove_ events).

* HOST_PORT
* HOST_PROTOCOL
* HOST_SERVICE
* HOST_VULNERABILITY
* HOST_CERT_ASSOCIATION

### `HOST_PORT`

Events of this type relate to the ports on a host attributed to your organization.

* **Subtype `ADD`** - A new port was added to an IP.

* **Subtype `REMOVE`** - A port was removed from an IP.

##### Cascading Event Types That Could Follow a Port Event

Subtype would match the Port event.

* HOST_PROTOCOL
* HOST_SOFTWARE
* HOST_VULNERABILITY
* HOST_CERT_ASSOCIATION

### `HOST_PROTOCOL`

Events of this type are related to the application-layer protocol(s) or protocol category detected on an open port.

* **Subtype `ADD`** - A protocol or protocol category was added to an IP.

* **Subtype `REMOVE`** - A previously seen protocol or protocol category was removed from an IP.

##### Cascading Event Types That Could Follow a Service Event

Subtype would match the Service event.

* HOST_SOFTWARE
* HOST_VULNERABILITY

### `HOST_SOFTWARE`

Events of this type relate to the software packages and versions reported by a service during a Censys scan of an IP.

* **Subtype `ADD`** - A software package was added to an IP.

* **Subtype `REMOVE`** - A software package was removed from an IP.

##### Cascading Event Types That Could Follow a Port Event

* HOST_VULNERABILITY

### `HOST_VULNERABILITY`

Events of this type relate to the presence of vulnerabilities in your organization's in-use software, as gathered from the [Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures list](https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/search).

* **Subtype `ADD`** - A vulnerability was found for a host.

* **Subtype `REMOVE`** - A vulnerability was removed from a host.

* **Subtype `CHANGE`** - The information about a vulnerability was changed.

### `HOST_CERT`

Events of this type record the presentation of your organization's certificates by your hosts during a TLS handshake with a Censys scanner.

* **Subtype `ADD`** - A certificate was linked to an IP.

* **Subtype `REMOVE`** - The link between a certificate and IP was removed.

### `CERTIFICATE`

Events of this type are related to the inclusion or exclusion of TLS certificates in your organization's attack surface.

* **Subtype `ASSOCIATE`** - A certificate was attributed to your organization.

* **Subtype `DISASSOCIATE`** - This event is only generated if there are no longer any connections between a certificate and other assets belonging to your organization.

##### Cascading Event Types That Could Follow a Certificate Event

* HOST_CERT

### `DOMAIN`

Events of this type record the inclusion or exclusion of apex domains in your organization's attack surface.

* **Subtype `ADD`** - An apex domain was added to your organization.

* **Subtype `REMOVE`** - An apex domain was removed from your organization.

##### Cascading Event Types That Could Follow a Certificate Event

* DOMAIN_EXPIRATION_DATE
* DOMAIN_REGISTRAR
* DOMAIN_MAIL_EXCHANGE_SERVER
* DOMAIN_NAME_SERVER

### `DOMAIN_EXPIRATION_DATE`

Events of this type capture the expiration date of an apex domain attributed to your organization.

* **Subtype `ADD`** - An expiration date was found for a domain.

* **Subtype `REMOVE`** - An expiration date for a domain was removed from your organization.

* **Subtype `CHANGE`** - The expiration date of an apex domain was changed.

### `DOMAIN_REGISTRAR`

Events of this type capture the Registrar of an apex domain attributed to your organization.

* **Subtype `ADD`** - A registrar was added to a domain.

* **Subtype `REMOVE`** - The registrar for a domain was removed from your organization.

* **Subtype `CHANGE`** - The registrar for an apex domain was changed.

### `DOMAIN_MAIL_EXCHANGE_SERVER`

Events of this type relate to mail exchange servers found in MX records in the DNS for an apex domain attributed to your organization.

* **Subtype `ADD`** - A mail exchange server was found for a domain.

* **Subtype `REMOVE`** - A mail exchange server was removed from a domain.

### `DOMAIN_NAME_SERVER`

Events of this type relate to name servers found in the DNS for an apex domain attributed to your organization.

* **Subtype `ADD`** - A DNS name server was found for a domain.

* **Subtype `REMOVE`** - A name server was removed from a domain.

### `DOMAIN_HOSTNAME`

Events of this type relate to the inclusion and exclusion of fully qualified domain names in your organization's attack surface.

* **Subtype `ADD`** - A hostname was added for a domain.

* **Subtype `REMOVE`** - A hostname was removed for a domain.

item.description:
# Introduction
Seeding the Censys Platform with known assets helps customers make the most of its powerful scanning and attributing capabilities. With known and claimed assets to start from, the Censys platform does a better job of mapping the true extent of a customer's digital footprint across the entire Internet.

## Asset Types

1. Autonomous System Number: `ASN`
1. CIDR Block: `CIDR`
1. Domain: `DOMAIN_NAME`
1. IP Address: `IP_ADDRESS`

## Asset Labels

Labels are similar to tags in that they group alike assets together, and enable programmatic replacement of seeds that change often, such as dynamically assigned IP addresses.

Censys highly recommends using labels for seeds if frequent updates to the seed list is planned.
